    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.27.24-25_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">24</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Jan.21, 1959.</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear JOhn<sic>John</sic>:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Thank you; for your prompt reply to my letter. I was a<del>b</del><add>n</add>xiously awaiting it. I believe I understand, more than many, what she meant to you. I think I can see that she came to you at a critical time in your life and that much of your success was due to her sympathetic understanding. She was a wonderful <hi rend="underline">woman</hi>. Words are inadequate tools, John, especially in my hands. I want to believe, and there is just as<del>s</del> muc<del>k</del><add>h</add> evidence for as against, that the anxiety I felt about yo<del>y</del><add>u</add>, during the past few months, came from an unexplainable enination that transcended words.</p>
                
                <p>In:re "Words": did you see the article "How Words <del>c</del><add>C</add>hange Our Lives" in the Dec.27, issue of The Saturday Evening Post. If availabl<del>r</del><add>e</add>, believe you would enjoy it. As I recently wrote my nephew, Jim, the "onl<del>t</del><add>y</add> thing you can be sure <add><hi rend="underline">of the</hi></add> reaction to a word uttered, written or oral; it will never be <hi rend="underline">exactly</hi> the same as yours." "Dedication is one of the finist<sic>finest</sic> wor<del>e</del><add>d</add>s in the English language." Jim is Floyd's oldest boy. He is Associate Professor of History at Kansas State and has. I think, a pretty good mind. Shortly after he went to Manhatten, he became very well aquainted "Jim" Casement, "Champion Track-layer" during the building of the <hi rend="caps">U.P.</hi> railroad. He, Jim Carey, is now working On<sic>on</sic> the reporting and anylizing<sic>analyzing</sic> of an interesting exchsnge<sic>exchange</sic> of letters between Casement and William Allen White, the "Sage of Emporia".</p>
                
                <p>I have just started reading a reprint by the Univ. of Okla. of "Capt." James <hi rend="caps">H.</hi> Cook's "Fifty Years on the Old Frontier". I recall that, at the o<del>l</del><add>n</add>ly time I saw him, on a trip to his Agate Springs ranch, he was well aquinted<sic>aquainted</sic>, at least, with your name.</p>
                
                <p>I wrote Dr. Aly (Mrs. or Miss?) also to Miss Carr.</p>
                
                <p>You are busy, John, so do not feel obligated to answering my letters promptly; when you have the urge and the time, just drop me a line.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours</salute> <signed>Rex</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
